<Pics>None</Pics>< Review>
This nail salon upset me. The manager/receptionist/head pimp nail lady seemed perturbed that my 14 year old stepdaughter was the one getting nails done (do they not do teenagers?). When the lady came over to ask us about colors, I asked about my nails about getting just a manicure with my short nails (I'm a nail biter) She mumbled a barely audible, "I don't know..." and then said, "I'll be right back. Hold on." then goes to help ladies that came in. She completely forgot about me even though I'm sitting right here and staring at her. Also, she seemed annoyed that people would just walk in. I guess since they are busy she turned a few people away but the way she told them to come back was so... abrupt.. Like... If you're going to be the head pimp nail lady, how about you learn customer service skills. So disappointing.

Having said all that... The teen's acrylic tips came out very nice. The upcharges added up very quickly (is it really necessary to charge $15 for gel color), the salon is nice and clean and the music very relaxing.

The location is in a shopping center with ample parking.< /Review>

< review>
After three years of being a recipient of the service we have learned a lot about Cambrian. We had a lot of trouble with their caregivers. One caregiver worked for us for two years. We, as the recipient of the service, are accountable. The caregivers themselves were not very accountable. Good caregiving is really hard work but most of the caregivers from Cambrian weren't good at their job with little or no experience. A few were argumentative and menacing. Good caregivers are not being paid enough or being given enough hours to make the transportation time, if on the bus, around the city sustainable. Travel time should be compensated. Cambrian is not accountable to us, as the recipient, or to the caregiver. They read the notes they have taken regarding our account to the caregiver. Do not expect privacy laws to followed by the staff at Cambrian. Largely. Cambrian fails in their duties of communicating to either recipient or caregiver. Misundetstandings happened alot because of this and Cambrian always blamed someone else for any misunderstanding.Overall, at the most vulnerable time when you need real caregivers Cambrian provides questionable service. If you have to use them go ahead and lock up your valuables. Don't expect the workers to be good at caregiving. Double check all communication between you and the caregiver. Don't leave your home unattended with the caregiver and the recipient. We were told by a coordinator at Cambrian that we weren't to trust any of their caregivers. Cambrian will blame the recipient for mistakes that their service provides. If this is a for profit company all of their resources are going into the pockets of the owners and not to the job of providing a good homecare service. It also seems as if the staff at their offices are overworked as well. This is our experience and a little advise.
Update: Cambrian entered a false statement into our medical records accusing us of having animal feces all over our floor. There is no truth to that accusation. Cambrian has proven to be completely inadequate as a provider of quality homecare services. And apparently if you complain about their services, as we did, they have no problem retaliating against you. Stay away from this home care agency.
Update: We were advised by our medical provider to try Cambrian one more time. Cambrian sent a caregiver, we believe, to catch us at something. APS was called, we don't know what the accusation was this time, but it was good because authorities could see that there was no truth to the accusations however Cambrian seems to be harassing us.We've complained and Cambrian didn't like that. If you don't have to use Cambrian Homecare service...don't. They don't help and have caused harm.</review>

<date>1513288202063<//date><rate>5<//rate><Review>Hiring a caregiver 101. Due diligence! Caregivers are givers of care, not dealers of cash. The bare bones salary is below living wages for most people. Consider our pay a supplement to care for the family we have to support as well. That said KNOW YOUR NEEDS! Do you tell the agency exactly what you want from  your special needs caregiver?
Here's my list.
Speak English.
Safty first CPR First aid certification
Self starter
Critical thinker
Transporter
Medical assistance
Energetic
Light to medium housework EVERY TIME
No cell phone compulsives please
Kind and patient
Reliable
Do you think that for $10.50 an hour you will find all that? I'm going to say "meh" but you have a chance of finding it at Cambrian. My experience with the company has been extremely positive. If your looking for a permanent solution,  check everywhere.  Even Craig's list. Caregivers are primarily independent contractors. We enjoy flexibility, the ability to pick and choose. While you evaluate us we are evaluating you. Does your house look like an episode of Horders?!? Does it wreak of dirty diaper and rotton food? Do you provide such little support for the caregiver as to insist all parties involved are to remain trapped inside the filthy mess of your life the entire length of stay. Not even fresh air or clean surroundings?
Seriously? Many families are in a huge amount of need. I get it, my mom is 82 and I care for her as well. Cambrian respite is wonderful if you know how to manage them. Make a list, check it twice. The State pays for most of our salary, (imagine a more cold and distant employer.) The staff at Cambrian works hard to find a good fit for  your needs. As far as my experience they will not stop until you are taken care of. We have work ethic and are proud of our work. It is the commitment to care that is shared up the chain of command.
So before you judge take a deep breath, is the plank in your eye so large you can not see the sliver in your Caregivers? Yes, some of us even have morals, standards and ethics that are at least as high as yours.  Like your loved one, we have feelings too. Most of us love what we do, it is our essence. Please try not to stamp out our fire. We're the ones who will be wiping your bottoms. Cambrian is quality care, excellent service and most are professional. I am also a CNA with vast experience in Geriactric and Devopmental special needs care. I work with all types of tramatic brain Injury. Gourmet cook,life skills coach etc. Good luck and don't forget to include Cambrian on your search for the perfect caregiver. BTW be prepared because someone with the qualifying experience you want usually starts at $15.00 to  $20.00 an hour thought a private source and more for an agency.<//Review>< Pics>

<Text>Very unprofessional experience just now.  I write a lot so if TL:DR these are the three most upsetting points:

- I called to check in as soon as I arrived (curbside service), then waited in my car for twenty minutes.  When I called back, they didn't know I was here (?)
- I was not allowed to come in with my pet due to COVID-19, but had not been told this at any point in advance of the appointment, and it was not indicated on the website.
- As I waited, I saw an employee with no face covering stick his head into another customer's car and talk to them for an extended period of time.

My experience:
I made an appointment online.  I showed up with my dog between 5 and 10 minutes early for our appointment, parked, and walked her to the dog side entrance, where I found the door was locked, but there was a sign indicating that I should return to my car and call for curbside service.  I was surprised, because I hadn't been told anything about curbside, but I did as instructed.

I waited about ten minutes.  My appointment time came and went.  I called back, but no one answered, so I left a voicemail.  As I waited, I saw clinic employees bringing pets out to cars, and it started to dawn on me that by "curbside," they meant that I wouldn't be allowed in with my pet at all.  One of the employees, a younger looking guy with red hair, was not wearing any type of face covering and I watched as he stuck his head completely inside a customer's car to have a conversation with them.  If I was expected to follow such rigid COVID-19 cautionary measures, why were the clinic's employees not even following basic ones?

It got to be 15 minutes past my appointment time when I finally got a call from the clinic.  The person on the phone said, "I got your voicemail, you're here?"  I'd been here at least twenty minutes at this point and had called and said so when I'd first arrived.  She apologized and explained that they'd been busy with other customers.  Okay, but I had an appointment at a particular time, and I haven't even been checked in yet.  Then I asked her to confirm that I would not be allowed in the clinic with my dog.  She said that was indeed the case.  Now, I have no problem with COVID-19 precautions, but trusting strangers with your pet without your supervision is a big ask, and I had not been told this information at any step in my appointment process.  There's a link on the website about a "Covid-19 Update," but at the time of writing it says "Drop-off appointments are also available where you are able to drop off your pet without having to enter the hospital ie your pet would be transferred to a staff member from the parking lot and we would contact you after exam for further treatment, if indicated" which sounds optional, not mandatory.

At no point was I told I'd be expected to let my pet go to her appointment alone.  She has pretty severe separation anxiety due to being abandoned as a puppy.  This was just a check-up, and it was in no way necessary to put her through the anxiety of not only having to go to the vet but having to do so alone.  If I'd been told about this policy in advance, it wouldn't be an issue.  I'd have simply postponed the appointment or sought an appointment elsewhere with a different policy.  I asked the woman on the phone why I hadn't been told, and she just said "There are signs on the door."  Not helpful.  I canceled the appointment.<//Text><gmapID>0x808e402062b6c6b1:0x1a2866a1f5111a35< /gmapID><resp>{'time': 1602713487078, 'text': 'Hi Rachel, We are sorry for the confusion & unpleasant experience with us. < Review>
My BMW X5 was delivered to automotive solutions by mistake.  It was supposed to go to BMW of San Francisco. < Text>
Pat, Bela, and their team has kept my BMW running like new despite its 190,000+ miles. They're truly experts on all types of cars and deeply committed to their customers.

On my latest visit, my battery had died, and my first text as always was to Pat. His shop uses text to message customers which is convenient and incredibly fast. Within minutes Pat let me know that, despite my failed attempts at jumpstarting, I should let AAA take a shot because they can put more juice in. Sure enough, the battery started, and I was able to take the car up to SF for Pat to take a look. He wanted to check the battery's health and make sure there was no parasitic drainage. He noted that the battery I had (installed in the trunk on my BMW) was the wrong size and was drained but luckily there was no problem with the electrical system in my car. While replacing the battery, his tech noted that the radiator was cracked and my belt tightener was broken. Pat graciously provided a loaner, and I returned two days later with my BMW in perfect condition.

Instead of getting saddled with new car payments, with San Francisco Automotive Solutions, I expect to keep driving my ultimate driving machine well past the 200,000 mile mark!</Text>

<Resp>None</Resp>< text>
Decent Asian Food, Affordable Prices

We got takeout here over two weekday nights. Not too long a wait.

First night: Ordered the tomato beef chow mein which was quite nice. Sizable portion too. Second night: Ordered the fish as well as pork with century egg porridge. The pork and century egg one tasted better. The fish porridge is quite bland. Also got the salt and pepper squid, and steamed pork dumplings. The mister seemed to like the squid. I didn't eat any. The dumplings were very average. Almost like supermarket types.

Average food but affordable prices.<//text>

< user>
112014242728123982922<//user>
<username>Jeff Dinakar</username>< Time>
1540522599791<//Time>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<review>Lotus House might be the restaurant that I frequented most often during my time at Berkeley... but let me explain! Lotus House was, and remains to this day one of my favorite joints because it doesn't pretend to be more than what it is, and what it is is a great value Chinese Restaurant. It's not overhyped like some of the other options in Berkeley, so generally it's not too packed. Also, there's plenty of options here for everyone, both Vegetarian and Non-Vegetarian. My go-to dish is Chicken Fried Rice, with a few scoops of the Chili flakes in oil that are available in the restaurant.

There's a good amount of seating in the restaurant, and it generally doesn't take long for you to get your food, just at the right balance between too fast to be legit and so slow that it reminds you of your hunger.

The staff is very friendly, and the main cashier is a really nice dude. Over my tenure of going here, he definitely got to know my face and what I'd order, to the point where once I'd walk into the restaurant, he'd say "The usual?" (This is one of my proudest accomplishments, real talk). Lotus house also offers takeout that you can order by phone, which became a regular feature for my weekly routine (when I'd stop by he'd know that I was the one who called to order, don't worry).

I stopped by the restaurant again after a few years and the main cashier still remembers me! It meant a crazy amount to me and Lotus House will always hold a dear place in my heart

Overall, I'll just say don't sleep on Lotus House, it's a hidden gem in Berkeley that I make sure to visit whenever I'm back (or do sleep on it if you want, I like the fact that it's never too packed!).<//review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None</response><GmapID>0x80857c2f6b2ce575:0x4df15241dc6c7d52<//GmapID></record>
</dataset><record>

<userid>102982781286577770400<//userid><Name>Maria Curley<//Name>< date>
1620113671784< /date>
<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>B Patisserie was an instant, addictive hit when it first opened several years ago. I simply couldn't resist chef Belinda Leong's elevated takes on viennoiserie and pastries, particularly the kouign amanns which were out of this world.

I hadn't visited for quite some time, so when I saw that Belinda had come up with special offerings just for Chinese New Year, I knew I had to try them before they were gone. The items I tried, whether the matcha tiramisu, the black sesame kouign amann, or the tiger sugar tapioca pudding, were very much in line with B Patisserie's regular, everyday offerings, only with Asian flavors that, in general, tend to be more subtle and less overpoweringly sweet than traditional Western sweets and pastries.

The matcha tiramisu, for example, had just enough green tea flavor in it, but not so much as to feel artificial or overwhelming. Same went for the tiger sugar tapioca pudding and even the black sesame kouign amann, although in the latter case it felt quite a bit smaller than the kouign amanns I'd enjoyed when B Patisserie first opened.

In any case, this is still world-class stuff, as Belinda's James Beard award attests. Despite her celebrity and success (a budding empire evidenced not only by B Patisserie's expanded store footprint but also by new ventures like B on the Go and Routier), you can still paparazzi her while she's hard at work in the open prep area, just behind the display cases. Keep up the great work, especially in representing the Bay Area's food scene on a national and even global scale, Belinda!<//Text><pictures>[{'url': <user_name>Tegan Tigani<//user_name>< Text>
We had to wait for about 15 minutes on a Sunday morning, but definitely worth it! However, if you know what you want, there is an expedited order online and pick-up option. Chocolate kouign aman was very flaky with drippy chocolate, so not the right choice if you're wearing something fancy or trying to eat in a dignified manner, but it was so tasty!!! Chocolate croissant had an almost coffecake-like topping--not the traditional pain au chocolate, but definitely a pleasure. Coffee service was quick and drinks were delicious; I appreciated that there are oat milk lattes. Staff did a fantastic job managing flow safely to ensure social distancing, and they were also very friendly.<//Text>

<user>104440412157462190193< /user>< Review>
My husband and I went here during our vacation and totally loved it! The bakery is welcoming and although Covid has changed things and you generally have to wait outside for your turn, the line went quickly and each employee was kind, welcoming and helpful. I was very impressed by each employee and the efficient and calm matter that they seemed to work in.
For our first time we got the Kouign Amann, the ginger molasses cookie and a hazelnut chocolate cake. The hazelnut chocolate cake left a little to be desired for me, the balance of flavors felt off but not a bad cake, just didn't stand out. On the other hand, my husband LOVED the Kouign Amann, it was wonderfully flakey and fresh, I was able to snatch a bite or two and agree that it was amazing. The ginger molasses cookie was my favorite and frankly, perfectly done, in my opinion. It was soft and chewy in the center, lightly crispy on the outside, had a beautiful light crunch from the sugar crystals and a fantastic balance of ginger and sweetness. I love ginger cookies but rarely are they done as well as the ones I got at b. Patisserie. We went back the very next day, ordered the Kouign Amann and Ginger cookie again and both were just as well done as the day before. I also ordered an almond banana chocolate crossiant for my mom which I gave her two days later when we went to visit, I had a bite myself and it tasted delicious! I can only imagine how good it must have tasted fresh! Lovely bakery, 5 stars without question, we hope to come again in the future.</Review>

<Review>If you want to taste some of the best desserts and vienoisserie the Bay Area has to offer.

With your "squad" for a foodie photoshoot for the  'gram...this isn't the kind of venue for all that nonsense. People here like to eat, not play with their food. If you MUST, get your order to go, then do your business OUTSIDE. There's better lighting anyway LOL!!!

B Patisserie is the best of the best in the Bay Area and always a must when I return to my other home away from home (Napa Valley)
On our most recent visit, we had our usual favorites- Chocolate and Classic Kougin Amann,  Passionfruit Bostock, and  Chocolate Chip Cookie. Another must is Chef Belinda Leong's desserts. This time,  we had the Chocolate Cream Cheese Budino, Black Sesame,  and Pumpkin Cheesecake. Always delicious, always consistent.

Another great thing to see is Chef Leong actually working alongside her pastry cooks, which was the case in every one of our visits in the past. VERY respectable,  considering you  rarely see the actual owner hustling with their staff on a  daily basis nowadays. You know what they say..."Teamwork makes the dream work!" She most definitely has a solid team behind her, and it shows.

It's always just been coffee and sweets for us, until we saw the table next to us enjoying the Ham and Cheese Tartine, so of course,  we had to try it(and it was BOMB!!!)and now it has become part of our hit list on every future visit to our favorite Patisserie in San Francisco.  ALOHA!!!

vienoisserie the Bay Area has to offer.

With your "squad" for a foodie photoshoot for the  'gram...this isn't the kind of venue for all that nonsense. People here like to eat, not play with their food. If you MUST, get your order to go, then do your business OUTSIDE. There's better lighting anyway LOL!!!

B Patisserie is the best of the best in the Bay Area and always a must when I return to my other home away from home (Napa Valley)
On our most recent visit, we had our usual favorites- Chocolate and Classic Kougin Amann,  Passionfruit Bostock, and  Chocolate Chip Cookie. Another must is Chef Belinda Leong's desserts. This time,  we had the Chocolate Cream Cheese Budino, Black Sesame,  and Pumpkin Cheesecake. Always delicious, always consistent.

Another great thing to see is Chef Leong actually working alongside her pastry cooks, which was the case in every one of our visits in the past. VERY respectable,  considering you  rarely see the actual owner hustling with their staff on a  daily basis nowadays. You know what they say..."Teamwork makes the dream work!" She most definitely has a solid team behind her, and it shows.

It's always just been coffee and sweets for us, until we saw the table next to us enjoying the Ham and Cheese Tartine, so of course,  we had to try it(and it was BOMB!!!)and now it has become part of our hit list on every future visit to our favorite Patisserie in San Francisco.  ALOHA!!!

You can't go wrong with the kouign amann. This is the place to go in SF for that pastry. <UserId.>112052219908680563744</UserId.>< user_name>
Joanna T</user_name>
<Time>1560779778341< /Time><Rating>5< /Rating><review>Although there are many bakeries in San Francisco, few capture the quintessential experience of France that b patisserie achieves.
Here Belinda Leong, pastry chef extraordinaire and co-owner, works her magic. Laminated pastry dough is her medium.

The item she is most famous for is the kouign amann. The classic Breton pastry has layers of flaky pastry and caramelized sugar rolled into the shape of a Breton cap.
Leong makes the classic and an abundance of other flavors such as chocolate (to die for) and exotic flavors such as black sesame and passionfruit (my favorite).
Of course, other pastries shine here as well. There‚Äôs the banana chocolate croissant, the almond croissant, a stellar chocolate shard cookie. The baguette and the levain bread are both outstanding.

For ambiance, the cafe is chic reminiscent of Paris, mirrors on white walls through which you can admire the reflection of the baked goods or other patrons.

There is light fare for lunch. Sandwiches or salad. If you care for more on a slightly heavier scale, cross the street to B on the Go, her other casual dining cafe.

Outside the cafe is a parklet if you‚Äôd prefer to eat outdoors to take advantage of fine weather or sun.

When you come to b patisserie, imagine yourself in France enjoying fine food and decor. Relax. There is no more French-style cafe here in the City. Bon Appetit!<//review>< Pictures>

<rate>2</rate><resp>None<//resp><user_id>101604334147734489484< /user_id><Review>Came to b. Patisserie looking for a great French croissant in San Francisco.  While their croissant is not great, it is also not the worst ever. The is color, layering and finish. Bit all are a bit lacking except the color. For example, layering though extant, was a little poor and resulted in the product leaning towards a bread crescent rolls than a nice croissant. The crust, though browned, was soft instead of crisp. At $3.25 the value for the b. Patisserie croissant is middle low. I'd settle for in a pinch after drunken night out, but would head to one of my other places to get a French croissant made with artistry.

As for a direct comparison to actual French croissants experienced multiple times since 1992, b. Patisserie needs some work and some refresher training in a art of a perfect croissant.

Paired my croissant with a cappucino.  Decent cappucino but next time I am going to ask for more potency, and more heat.

The location is excellent and cut. A great place to relax for breakfast or lunch.  Large and clean windows to watch the world go by. Comfortable chairs and benches both inside, and caf√© style on the sidewalk to take in the sun.

Even though b. Patisserie is not my ideal croissant place I look forward to a return to enjoy some tarts and sandwiches sometime in the future.< /Review></record></dataset><record>

Awesome pastries.  Our favorites are too many to list.  Go to favorite if we want something heavy and satisfying is the chocolate banana almond croissant.  But for light fare we really like the kouign amann Regular, the chocolate, and then the other variants that seem to come and go (raspberry, black sesame, pumpkin (must be seasonal) ... These flavors are more subtle ).  There seems to always be a line but never too long to wait.  Pretty good about covid-19 safety protocols.<//text>

A solid well deserved 5 stars for this French patisserie in SF. <UserId.>116873293890878667540<//UserId.><Name>Brittney Pan</Name><time>1542252651855</time><rate>3< /rate>< Review>
This is my favorite pastry store. However,  the quality was not as stable as before. I hope they can keep the quality at the same level. I drive at least 40 mins one way to buy the pastry. I got disappointed for couple of times.
I was a fan Gary Danko's deserts. So when I knew the pastry chef opened a store herself, I knew the pastry will be good. I have tried most of items here. However, I found that only Kouign Amann Nature is my favorite. Other pastries are good but not as good as kouign amann. I don't quite like its cakes. Drinks are ok but pricey. Sandwiches are ok if you happen to be hungry here. You will have to be in line first to pick the items you want and pay then find a place to sit. Most of the time you can find a place to sit very quickly. The store is always packed.< /Review>

Jacqueline Telljohann< /Name>
< text>
I'm usually not a big pastry fan, but this place has me converted. We came here when traveling based off of a recommendation.

We tried the plum mixed berry kouigan-amann and the mixed berry almond croissant. They were both amazing and the best pastries I've ever had. The kouigan-amann was my favorite. I've never had anything like it! It was sweet, buttery, and delicious.

Service was fast‚Äîwe just picked out our pastries and paid at the counter.

This is a must try in San Francisco!< /text>

Kouign-amann ($4.25)
I visited on Christmas eve and it was really crowded  with people trying to buy christmas cakes. When I got there, Kouign-amann was sold out and the staff said it would take about 15 minutes to get one. I waited and got freshly baked one. In short, it was so great. < Review>
Reminds me of France; the smell and taste of freshly baked goods and the ambiance are exceptional! Yes, there are plenty of other bakeries in San Francisco, but none of them makes a better kouign amann than b.patisserie! A bit on the pricier side, but my-oh-my are their pastries worth the splurge (and more)! You have to taste it and experience the unbeliveable bliss of b. These pastries will blow your taste buds away and you will not settle for anything less than their quality. Absolutely love their chocolate banana croissant and kouign amann; they make them in classic flavors as well as seasonal flavors. Highly recommend!<//Review>

</dataset><record>
<Time>1518406623425</Time><text>B pats is a must try patisserie in the beautiful city of SF. In fact, once you've tried B you'll want to add it to your list of pitstops whenever you're in the mood for some sweet treats because it never disappoints! I love that the place is open concept so you can watch the pastry chefs /bakers/ artists at work. You can visit for the pastries of course, but if you're stomach is craving more than just sweets I've seen people go in for sandwiches and coffee too! However, if you're like me and you love buttery, flakey, crispy pastries, their kouign‚Ä¢amann is to die for! Whether it's the plain, chocolate, or seasonal flavored one, it always puts a smile on my face.. I'm drooling just thinking about it. The cookies are that perfect crispy-chewy scrumptious many of us seek, and their cakes, tarts, mousses, and other sweet treasures are decadent to the point that just closing your eyes and taking that first bite will whisk you off to paradise. In short, this place is dangerously good, so stop by if you can resist the temptations of purchasing one of everything. Good luck, future visitors!<//text>< gmapID>

< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< Review>
One of the most famous bakeries in the city, and I personally like it better than Tartine.
Known for kouign amann, which is the French, round shaped, caramelized croissant. Loaded with butter and caramelized sugar, but indeed worthy of the sin even for the most health conscious people.
The store is busy but well organized. You pick up your items while waiting in line, then proceed to the check out. There is free, self served water, along with first come first serve small tables. For the times I've come, I can always sit down and enjoy my kouign amann in 5 minutes or so. That's also much better than the 20-30 min wait at Tartine.
Btw the menu is outdated. Most items are 25 to 50 cents more expensive, as of August 2017. Original kouign amann is $4.25 now.<//Review>

< text>
I mean... How can you not LOVE b? This is probably my favorite patisserie in SF hands down. The pastries are wonderfully laminated, the combinations are varied, inventive, and fresh, and the flavors are well balanced. Throw in a great coffee and I just can't imagine having a better Saturday morning. You just gotta go early because it can get crazy pretty quickly. Usually if you're there before nine, you'll be fine. But that can change on a dime.<//text>

< text>
My favorite bakery in the city... And no I'm not biased cuz I use to live around the corner.

While they're known for their kouign amanns and they're amazing, I have a soft spot for their banana chocolate croissants. Those are so amazing.

Be prepared. This place is always busy so good luck finding a spot to sit. They have a small seating area outside for those with pets but those spots are hard to snag in peak times as well.<//text>

< review>
I'm French so I know a bunch about patisserie. Well I can say that B Patisserie is a fine place. What they are doing there is fantastic, from the basic croissant to the elaborated cakes, everything I've tried so far was fantastic.

Prices are high but I'd say reasonable for the quality, keep them as they are!

We love to go there with friend to have coffee on the very French looking take and enjoy some sweets. Unfortunately it became hard to find a spot as the place is getting more and more popular, classic story.

If you are into pastries, that's, in my humble opinion, the best place in the city< /review>

< Text>
Arrived around 10am. Standing room only and the line wasn't quite out the door. Timed it perfectly as by the time we left, just a few minutes after arrival, the line was out the door and heading down the block. What to say about this place? Their specialty is Kougin Amman, which I ordered 2 regulars and 1 special with strawberry and rhubarb. The KAs are incredible--my only point of reference is Dominique Ansel's DKA and I think b patisserie's are better (lighter, greater contrast between the sweet and the savory). Also ordered a chocolate croissant for my daughter and a almond apricot peach crossaint. Oh, damn, can't forget the cinnamon roll or the baguette. The croissants were melt-in-your-mouth beautiful and the cinnamon roll is off the chain--I love hint of citrus (orange zest?!?). The shop is organized so you can sit, if there is space, or easily take your lovelies to go. The line parades you in front of the pastries and an employee grabs what you need. The few people I spoke with were very friendly and thankful. This is a good point at which to end this review as I need to go work off the 750+ calories I just consumed.</Text>

The food here is to die for -- I think their products embody baked good perfection (similar to Tartine). Why only 4 stars? The line is usually out the door, so you'll likely wait 20-30 minutes to order. This detracts enough from the experience that I don't come here unless I really have a hankering; most of the time, I'll opt for something easier. Still, it is worth coming here once in awhile to remind yourself of what true artistry can achieve.<//review>

The light little space boasts a beautiful counter packed with an impressive array of both savory and sweet treats. Of course the iconic kouign-amann reigns supreme, but everything else, including cheddar-apple scones and simplistic croissants are worthy of your order. <Rating>5</Rating><review>B Patisserie make the best Kouginon Aman!! As you walk in this cafe/restaurant, you are greeted by a line of freshly baked goods.  You won't even know where to start as they all look amazing!  They're like croissants stuffed with a sugary glazed. You have the option to get the  chocolate and seasonal fruit flavors as well.  All under $4.  There is savory pastries like bacon/cheddar scones and ham/cheese croissants.

There is also seating for breakfast and lunch.  Parking could be spotty as it's located near the Divisadero corridor.   Definitely worth checking out!< /review>< pictures>

<Name>Michelle Hall<//Name><date>1412619968146</date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Text>
Upon first walking in to this bakery, I wasn't exactly sure how they were taking orders. There were a lot of people on that Saturday morning that I stepped inside. Lots of light and seating available and glass beautiful display case of all the gorgeous baked goods is what you are greeted with when you walk in. This place has been on my list for several months and was recommended by a co-worker friend of mine that urged me to go since I raved about all the delicacies that I found in travels in France, Germany, Italy. This is definitely a French bakery and it exceeded my expectations. I ordered a little box to be shared with my husband. The kouign amanns were just that amazing...flakey, crispy, the right amount of sweet, buttery goodness all wrapped up into one perfect pastry. I also ordered something that sounded very interesting: a pear, fig, almond filled croissant, which was also amazing. They serve four barrel coffee to go along with your desserts/pastries/breakfast. On the weekends, there is apparently more of a selection from I have been told and will check it out during a weekday to see what their selection is like.< /Text>

< review>
Oh, this place is no good for a diet but I'm not even upset about it.
So B. Patisserie is no longer a secret, people will wait in long lines at all times of the day just to order a pastry but it's well worth the wait and everyone knows that.
B.Patisserie has become a Saturday tradition. I stop by on my way to go hiking and order something delish. Half of the time I have no idea what exactly I'm ordering but I don't even care because it's always good. However, if you're a tourist who is limited to visiting once, you must try the kouign amann. Hands down divine.<//review>

< Text>
Easily one of the best bakeries in the city. They have many varied options for pastries and cakes that are made fresh daily. Their open face sandwiches, Tartines, are varied and usually pretty good - they don't start serving them until about 11am though. Coffee is excellent.

My favorites: Chocolate banana croissant, kougin amann, bostock

Though there is almost always a wait, the lines moves very fast.<//Text>

<Text>This is such a sweet place; not only are the pastries amazing (I had a Koiugn Amann nature and a strawberry almond croissant), but the staff were amazingly friendly and helpful. I asked which of the kouign amann were the most recently out of the oven, and after checking, told me the nature, i.e. without jam or other additions. This allowed me to sample the simple version, though it was far from simple! Ordering the strawberry almond croissant  allowed me to sample a fruity pastry, which the gal who waited on me advised was still warm from the oven, which it was, indeed, warm with a bright strawberry flavor, so good! There were all sorts of other things I'd love to try, including scones; maybe I can make it back another day while I'm visiting SF... < Review>
b. patisserie is an excellent place if you like pastries.  Belinda Leong makes many wonderful pastries.  My favorite is the grande macaroon.  Kouhn Amman is her specialty.  I enjoy spending a weekend morning sitting with my breakfast pastry and cup of tea here.  In the evening, a 10 hour apple tart is a great way to end your dinner.  Front of the House Candace and Johanna are warm and friendly to everyone who enters the premise.  They take the time to explain what each item is.  When you are there, take a look at the wall, there is a macaroon tree!  My kids would love to eat the art.< /Review>

< username>
Sapph Nor</username>
<Pics>None<//Pics>< user>
103499601184173589405<//user>
< Text>
Five stars for the service! The pastries, though, are a bit overrated. I've tried pretty much all the pastries. Some are really good and some are just average. Most are very rich, like the Chai Tart, so rich it can be a meal itself. At $6.5 per tart, hum...I'm not so sure.

The bakery certainly deserves the credit of being innovative and combining different ingredients/tastes in the same pastry, as in the green tea grapefruit pistachio tart and the coconut guava mango tart.

I'm a macaron fan, so I like how the macaron flavors are rotated often. However, sometimes they have the so-called "Mystery Flavors", and the staff couldn't even tell you what the flavors are. Or maybe they weren't supposed to?! A bit awkward not knowing what I was eating. The macarons are usually so sweet, that it's hard to tell what flavor it is. All the macarons I've tried are ganache filling.

Well, so much for the sweets (except for the quiche). The next time I go, maybe I'll start sampling the Tartines.</Text>

<pics>None<//pics><rate>5< /rate><review>Get: kouign amann, macarons. Those two items took me back to my summer in France. Legit.

I've pretty much tried everything here (hey, carbs cure my weekend hangovers, ok?) Everything is good, but nothing that stood out like the kouign amann and macarons.

KA - Flakey, crispy, melty, warm. Its not overly sweet like most places and its not flakey to the point of being dry (cough mr. holmes)
Macarons - THE BEST MACARON I'VE HAD OUTSIDE OF FRANCE. It is a crispy shell on the outside and a moist chewy cookie underneath. I'm drooling writing about this now.
QUICHE- Almost forgot about this amazing slice of heaven. Get it.

The cookies here are good, but not as chewy as I like (more of a thin crunchy cookie) The flavored croissants are a little too raw-dough-y in the middle for me. The cakes are good depending on the flavor (some flavors change the texture of the cake and make it a bit too dry)

But yes, that line is worth it.</review><UserId.>113936329263180050533<//UserId.>< date>

<Name>Lan N</Name><rating>5<//rating>< text>
Former Gary Danko pastry chef Belinda Leong knows what she's doing. Every pastry here is on point - the quality and expertise really shows. To avoid that feeling of missed opportunities, come here with a couple of friends so you can split a variety of baked goods. One thing that you MUST order is the Kouign (pronounced "Queen") Amann, a majestic pastry with golden crispy, flaky curves and a sweet glaze center. You will be humbled by its beauty. In terms of atmosphere, it's a charming bakery with an open kitchen and seating at the front of the shop. Feels very clean and cozy. A good place to enjoy some Four Barrel coffee and catch up with friends.< /text>

< review>
Former Gary Danko pastry chef Belinda Leong knows what she's doing. Every pastry here is on point - the quality and expertise really shows. To avoid that feeling of missed opportunities, come here with a couple of friends so you can split a variety of baked goods. One thing that you MUST order is the Kouign (pronounced "Queen") Amann, a majestic pastry with golden crispy, flaky curves and a sweet glaze center. You will be humbled by its beauty. In terms of atmosphere, it's a charming bakery with an open kitchen and seating at the front of the shop. Feels very clean and cozy. A good place to enjoy some Four Barrel coffee and catch up with friends.<//review>

<UserId.>114907595278616299758< /UserId.><username>Sonya Li<//username>< Date>
1405474583631< /Date>
< rate>
5< /rate>
< Review>
Kouign amann translates to butter cake in Breton and it‚Äôs exactly that - the outside is crusty and it‚Äôs a dense, caramely, moist, buttery, sweet cake. When I sat down with my order, I took the prerequisite 100 pictures like a good Asian and immediately ripped a chunk with my grubby hands and shoved it into my mouth like a savage. It was light and airy, buttery, the cardamom apricot filling was the bees knees, and the fine cinnamon sugar on top made it the perfect winter treat. It was amazing. When I finally looked up, I noticed that the beautiful woman sitting next to me was elegantly knifing and forking her baked good so I brushed the crumbs off my lips, crossed my legs, straightened my back, and smiled demurely like the lotus flower I am.

Even though I sought this place out to taste their kouign amann, I ended up sampling several other treats.

My partner ordered the apple brioche tart. It was almost like a baked donut, but with a smooth vanilla custard in the center under the baked apples. It was good and my partner loved it, but it‚Äôs not on my list of favorites.

We took home the bostock and we were told it was twice baked broche soaked in passion fruit and topped off with raspberries and almonds. It‚Äôs crusty, eggy, and you can taste the passion fruit. The raspberries added enough acid to make your mouth water and greedy for another bite while the passion fruit brought a tropical feel to the dessert.

We also took home the chocolate banana smores tart which was surprising good because I hate bananas in my desserts. They tend to be over ripened and I have a distain for the fermented taste. The chocolate wasn‚Äôt too heavy, but the crust was too hard and there wasn‚Äôt enough s‚Äômores for an even distribution of each element in evert bite.

If you visit, you‚Äôll find Belinda Leong working hard behind the counter and it just makes everything so much sweeter.< /Review>
